## What happened

.NET 11 removed the built-in DSA implementation on macOS. Apple's Security.framework dropped DSA support, and .NET no longer ships a managed fallback for that platform. Calling `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.

This was signaled by the `SYSLIB0028` obsolete warning in earlier versions.

## How to fix it

**Option A – Use OpenSSL explicitly (quick fix for verification-only):**

```csharp
// On macOS, use DSAOpenSsl backed by a locally-installed OpenSSL
using System.Security.Cryptography;

DSA dsa;
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    dsa = new DSAOpenSsl();   // requires OpenSSL installed (e.g. via Homebrew)
else
    dsa = DSA.Create();
```

You'll need the `System.Security.Cryptography.OpenSsl` package and OpenSSL on the macOS host (`brew install openssl`).

**Option B – Use BouncyCastle (no native dependency):**

```csharp
// Fully managed, works everywhere
var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
verifier.Init(false, publicKey);
verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
```

**Option C (recommended long-term) – Migrate away from DSA** to ECDSA or Ed25519, re-signing legacy artifacts where possible.

## Summary

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|----------|------|------|
| `DSAOpenSsl` | Minimal code change | Requires OpenSSL runtime on macOS |
| BouncyCastle | Fully managed, portable | Extra dependency |
| Migrate to ECDSA/Ed25519 | Modern, supported everywhere | Requires re-signing legacy data |

For a verification-only library, Option B (BouncyCastle) is the least-friction cross-platform path until you can retire DSA entirely.
